She laughed heartily at our Guarauy, and we, on the other hand, at her's.' For as this insulated family had no intercourse with any but themselveS, their language was most ridiculously corrupted. The youth had never seen a female except his mother and sister, nor any male but his father. The girl had seen no woman but her mother nor any man but her brother, her father having been torn to pieces by a tiger before she was born. To gather the fruits that grew on the ground or on the treeS, and wood for fuel, the dexterous girl ran over the forest tangled as it was with underwood‚ reeds, and brambleS, by which she had her feet wretchedly scratched. Not to go unattended, she commonly had a little parrot on her shoulder, and a small monkey on her arm, un- terrified by the tigers that haunt that neigh- bourhood. The new proselytes were quickly clothed in the town, and served with the daily allowance of food before the rest.
